In this issue&hellip;
The editor reflected on 2 years of Special Reserve: memberships had shot passed 25,000, with 5,500 of those also subscribing to Official Secrets (and, therefore, Confidential). While there had been the usual summer lull in game sales, they were expecting a bumper Xmas due to the Amiga&rsquo;s popularity and had decided to also carry Atari Lynx, Sega Megadrive and CDTV titles.
The news included details of SSI&rsquo;s &ldquo;Secret of Silver Blades&rdquo;, a bunch of upcoming flight sims, Alexey Pajitnov&rsquo;s &ldquo;Tetris&rdquo; followup &ldquo;Welltris&rdquo;, along with rumours of a new adventure from Level 9 (&ldquo;Billy the Kid&rdquo;), a game based on the book &ldquo;Neuromancer&rdquo;, and Sierra bringing &ldquo;King&rsquo;s Quest IV&rdquo; and &ldquo;Colonel&rsquo;s Bequest&rdquo; to the Amiga.

News I&rsquo;m guessing this was an April Fools joke, but the lead news story concerned PC game &ldquo;X-Wing&rdquo; appearing &ldquo;on&rdquo; the Amiga&hellip; as in, it was a photo of an &ldquo;X-Wing&rdquo; box sitting on an Amiga&hellip;
Mindscape revealed that their upcoming Gameboy platformer &ldquo;Alfred Chicken&rdquo; would be getting an Amiga release.
Ocean reckoned that the somewhat crowded car racer genre was in need of something with a bit more realism.

In this month&rsquo;s issue&hellip;
The subject on the editor&rsquo;s mind was, perhaps unexpectedly for an adventure gaming mag, taxation as he had a good rant about how much money from each game the club sold went to the HMRC.
Games making the news this month included several horror games (&ldquo;Elvira&rdquo;, [&ldquo;Demon&rsquo;s Tomb - The Awakening&rdquo;][4403], [&ldquo;Mystery of the Mummy&rdquo;][4404]), the next title from The Bitmaps in the form of [&ldquo;Cadaver&rdquo;][4405], and some new games from Origin.

Since getting back into the C64/Amiga scene, one of the things I&rsquo;ve really loved is that there are still people out there making &amp; publishing games for the machines. So I finally got around to picking up a few. From Psytronkik there is:
&ldquo;Kung Fu Maniacs Trilogy&rdquo; &ldquo;Gravitrix&rdquo; &ldquo;X-Force&rdquo; &ldquo;Space Trip 2086&rdquo;. And one from Pond that I had been eagerly awaiting:
&ldquo;The Bear Essentials&rdquo; These should keep me busy for a little while&hellip;
